# ChromaMark ‚Äî ecosystem

::: info What this is
Where ChromaMark plugs in today, and where it could go next. Written in ChromaMark
(dogfooding the format) ‚Äî open it in the VS Code preview or the playground.
:::

## Current state

::: success Available now
- **npm** ‚Äî `@chromamark/renderer` (a markdown-it plugin plus a browser/CDN bundle) and `@chromamark/cli` (`.cm` ‚Üí one self-contained HTML file, theme inlined, no CDN).
- **PyPI** ‚Äî `chromamark`: a markdown-it-py renderer with byte-identical HTML, a fluent `ChromaDoc` builder, and Jupyter `display_chromamark`.
- **VS Code** ‚Äî live preview, syntax highlighting, and a left-side outline for `.cm` files.
- **Playground** ‚Äî a split-pane live editor and preview, hosted on GitHub Pages.
- **Docs site** ‚Äî landing, spec, gallery, and playground on GitHub Pages.
- **LLMs** ‚Äî `docs/llms.txt`, a token-lean cheat sheet to drop into a system prompt.
:::

Every surface above is **full fidelity** ‚Äî the real CSS theme renders and adapts to
light/dark. Distribution is npm (`@chromamark/*`) and PyPI (`chromamark`).

## Possible future state

Ordered roughly by leverage. Not every surface can render the real theme, so some
need a translation layer.

| Idea | Effort | Approach |
| ---- | ------ | -------- |
| GitHub sanitized surfaces (README / PR / Actions) | [!warning Med] | transpile `.cm` ‚Üí Alerts + badge images |
| Code-fence highlighting in output | [!success Low] | wire the renderer's `highlight` hook to highlight.js / Prism |
| Sublime grammar | [!success Low] | reuse the TextMate grammar; highlighting only |
| Zed extension | [!warning Med] | tree-sitter grammar + a small Rust/WASM extension |
| JetBrains plugin | [!danger High] | full IDE plugin with a JCEF webview preview |
| Jekyll | [!warning Med] | JS-include on stock Pages, or CI prerender |
| MCP resource | [!success Low] | expose the spec + quick reference; optional render tool |

::: details info GitHub's two rendering tiers
**Pages** is a plain static host ‚Äî the full bundle works there today (that's the
current docs site). But **README, PR/issue comments, and Actions summaries** run
GitHub's sanitizer: no `<style>`, `class`/`id`, or `<script>`. The theme can't
render, so those surfaces would need a transpile to GitHub-native equivalents:
- colored blocks ‚Üí **Alerts** (`[!NOTE]` / `[!WARNING]` / `[!TIP]` / `[!CAUTION]`)
- pills and meters ‚Üí **badge images** (shields.io or self-hosted SVG)
- `::: details` ‚Üí native `<details>`; `::: fields` ‚Üí a table

Degraded but styled. Open choice: shields.io (easy, external) vs. self-hosted SVG.
:::

::: details info Jekyll's safe-mode catch
GitHub Pages builds Jekyll in safe mode, which disallows custom plugins ‚Äî so a
native Ruby `{% chromamark %}` tag only works if you build the site yourself in
Actions. On stock Pages, either drop the JS bundle into the theme (client-side) or
prerender with the CLI in CI.
:::
